<li id="cite_note-web-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-web_2-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation news">Day, Peter (17 December 1997). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/business/40033.stm">"Encyclopaedia Britannica changes to survive"</a>. BBC News<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 27 March 2007</span>. "Sales plummeted from 100,000 a year to just 20,000."</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.au=Day%2C+Peter&amp;rft.aufirst=Peter&amp;rft.aulast=Day&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopaedia+Britannica+changes+to+survive&amp;rft.date=17+December+1997&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fnews.bbc.co.uk%2F1%2Fhi%2Fbusiness%2F40033.stm&amp;rft.pub=BBC+News&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-encyclopaedia_1954-3"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-encyclopaedia_1954_3-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-encyclopaedia_1954_3-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-encyclopaedia_1954_3-2"><sup><i><b>c</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-encyclopaedia_1954_3-3"><sup><i><b>d</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation encyclopaedia">"Encyclopaedia". <i>Encyclopædia Britannica</i> (14th ed.). 1954.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.atitle=Encyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopaedia&amp;rft.date=1954&amp;rft.edition=14th&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span> Aside from providing an excellent summary of the <i>Britannica's</i> history and early spin-off products, this article also describes the life-cycle of a typical <i>Britannica</i> edition. A new edition typically begins with strong sales that decay as the encyclopaedia becomes outdated. When work on a new edition is begun, sales of the old edition stop, just when fiscal needs are greatest: a new editorial staff must be assembled, articles commissioned. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elkan_Harrison_Powell" title="Elkan Harrison Powell">Elkan Harrison Powell</a> identified this fluctuation of income as a danger to any encyclopaedia, one he hoped to overcome with continuous revision.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-EB_encyclopedia-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-EB_encyclopedia_4-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation encyclopaedia">"Encyclopedias and Dictionaries". <i>Encyclopædia Britannica</i> <b>18</b> (15th ed.). <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Encyclopædia_Britannica,_Inc." title="Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.">Encyclopædia Britannica, Inc.</a> 2007. pp.&#160;257–286.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.atitle=Encyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.btitle=Encyclopedias+and+Dictionaries&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft.edition=15th&amp;rft.genre=bookitem&amp;rft.pages=257%E2%80%93286&amp;rft.pub=Encyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica%2C+Inc.&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.volume=18" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
