<li id="cite_note-105"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-105">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation encyclopaedia"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.webcitation.org/5kwbm2bZC"><i>Encarta's Encyclopedia Article Center</i></a>. Archived from <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://encarta.msn.com/artcenter_0/Encyclopedia_Articles.html">the original</a> on 31 October 2009<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 11 April 2007</span>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.btitle=Encarta%27s+Encyclopedia+Article+Center&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fencarta.msn.com%2Fartcenter_0%2FEncyclopedia_Articles.html&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-Giles_Nature_study_2005-106"><span class="mw-cite-backlink">^ <a href="#cite_ref-Giles_Nature_study_2005_106-0"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href="#cite_ref-Giles_Nature_study_2005_106-1"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation journal"><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jim_Giles_(reporter)" title="Jim Giles (reporter)">Giles, J.</a> (2005). "Internet encyclopaedias go head to head". <i>Nature</i> <b>438</b> (7070): 900–1. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bibcode" title="Bibcode">Bibcode</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://adsabs.harvard.edu/abs/2005Natur.438..900G">2005Natur.438..900G</a>. <a href="Digital_object_identifier.html" title="Digital object identifier">doi</a>:<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://dx.doi.org/10.1038%2F438900a">10.1038/438900a</a>. <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/PubMed_Identifier" title="PubMed Identifier" class="mw-redirect">PMID</a>&#160;<a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/16355180">16355180</a>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.atitle=Internet+encyclopaedias+go+head+to+head&amp;rft.aufirst=J.&amp;rft.au=Giles%2C+J.&amp;rft.aulast=Giles&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=info%3Abibcode%2F2005Natur.438..900G&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1038%2F438900a&amp;rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F16355180&amp;rft.issue=7070&amp;rft.jtitle=Nature&amp;rft.pages=900%E2%80%931&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.volume=438" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span> <span class="plainlinks noprint" style="font-size:smaller"><a class="external text" href="http://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Template:Cite_doi/10.1038.2F438900a&amp;action=edit&amp;editintro=Template:Cite_doi/editintro2">edit</a></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-FBE-107"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-FBE_107-0">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation news">McHenry, Robert (15 November 2004). <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.tcsdaily.com/article.aspx?id=111504A">"The Faith-Based Encyclopedia"</a>. <i>TCS Daily</i>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.atitle=The+Faith-Based+Encyclopedia&amp;rft.aufirst=Robert&amp;rft.aulast=McHenry&amp;rft.au=McHenry%2C+Robert&amp;rft.date=15+November+2004&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.tcsdaily.com%2Farticle.aspx%3Fid%3D111504A&amp;rft.jtitle=TCS+Daily&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-108"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-108">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation web">Terdiman, Daniel. <a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://news.cnet.com/Study-Wikipedia-as-accurate-as-Britannica/2100-1038_3-5997332.html">"Study: Wikipedia as accurate as Britannica"</a>. <i>Staff Writer, CNET News</i>. CNET News<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 5 July 2011</span>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.atitle=Study%3A+Wikipedia+as+accurate+as+Britannica&amp;rft.aufirst=Daniel&amp;rft.aulast=Terdiman&amp;rft.au=Terdiman%2C+Daniel&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fnews.cnet.com%2FStudy-Wikipedia-as-accurate-as-Britannica%2F2100-1038_3-5997332.html&amp;rft.jtitle=Staff+Writer%2C+CNET+News&amp;rft.pub=CNET+News&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-109"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-109">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text"><span class="citation pressrelease"><a rel="nofollow" class="external text" href="http://www.nature.com/press_releases/Britannica_response.pdf">"Encyclopædia Britannica: a response"</a> (PDF). <i>Nature</i> (Press release). 23 March 2006<span class="reference-accessdate">. Retrieved 21 October 2006</span>.</span><span title="ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AEncyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica&amp;rft.atitle=Encyclop%C3%A6dia+Britannica%3A+a+response&amp;rft.date=23+March+2006&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft_id=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.nature.com%2Fpress_releases%2FBritannica_response.pdf&amp;rft.jtitle=Nature&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal" class="Z3988"><span style="display:none;">&#160;</span></span></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-110"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-110">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Writings of Archibald Constable, as quoted on p. 58 of Frank Kafker and Jeff Loveland (eds), <i>The Early Britannica</i>, Oxford University Press, 2009. Constable estimated in 1812 that there had been 3,500 copies printed, but revised his estimate to 3,000 in 1821.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-111"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-111">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">According to Smellie, it was 10,000, as quoted by Robert Kerr in his "Memoirs of William Smellie." Archibald Constable was quoted as saying the production started at 5,000 and concluded at 13,000. All this information is found in the 14th edition of <i>Britannica</i>, Volume 8, in the article "Encyclopedia" on page 374.</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-112"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-112">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">This is stated in the 9th edition of <i>Britannica</i> in Volume VIII in the article "Encyclopedia".</span></li>
<li id="cite_note-113"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-113">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">in the 14th edition of <i>Britannica</i>, Volume 8, in the article "Encyclopedia" on page 376, it gives the numbers of 10,000 sets sold by Britannica plus 45,000 genuine American reprints by Scribner's Sons, and "several hundred thousand sets of mutilated and fraudulent 9th editions were sold..." Most sources estimate there were 500,000 pirated sets.</span></li>
</ol>
</div>
